column3: >Ground-glass appearance on HRCT is seen in which of the following conditions?

>Silicosis on HRCT shows a ground-glass appearance. Silicosis is due to the inhalation of crystalline silicon dioxide (silica) seen in individuals employed in sandblasting or rock mining. Macrophages phagocytose inhaled silica particles, thereby activating and releasing inflammatory mediators (IL-1, IL-8) that cause fibroblast recruitment. Microscopy reveals coalescent nodules of whorled collagen fibers surrounded by a peripheral zone of silica-laden macrophages. HRCT shows a ""crazy paving"" pattern due to interlobular septal thickening on the background of ground-glass opacity.

>Asbestosis: X-ray shows peripheral reticular opacities predominantly in the lower zones. It predominantly affects the lower lobes of the lung, in contrast to other forms of pneumoconiosis, which affect the upper lobes.
>N/A - This is the correct option. See 'Explanation' row.

>Anthracosis/coal workers' pneumoconiosis: This is a pulmonary condition seen in coal miners. The inhaled carbon pigment is engulfed by alveolar or interstitial macrophages, which accumulate in the connective tissue. Initially, it causes simple coal workers pneumoconiosis with little or no pulmonary dysfunction. With continued exposure, lung tissue undergoes progressive massive fibrosis which is called complicated coal workers pneumoconiosis. The upper lobes of the lungs are commonly involved. Simple coal workers' pneumoconiosis appears as small round nodular opacities with an occasional appearance of reticular or reticulonodular opacities. Compared to silicosis, the nodules in CWP tend to have less well-defined margins and a more granular appearance.

>Byssinosis: Caused by cotton dust, it can induce occupational asthma. It is characterized clinically by occasional (early-stage) and then regular (late-stage) chest tightness toward the end of the first day of the workweek - Monday chest tightness.

column11: >- Coal dust: Anthracosis, Macules, Progressive massive fibrosis, Caplan syndrome (Exposure: Coal mining (particularly hard coal))
column13: >- Silica: Silicosis, Caplan syndrome (Exposure: Metal casting work, sandblasting, hard rock mining, stone cutting, others)
column15: >- Asbestos: Asbestosis, Pleural plaques, Caplan syndrome, Mesothelioma, Carcinoma of the lung, larynx, stomach, colon (Exposure: Mining, milling, manufacturing, and installation and removal of insulation)
column17: >- Beryllium: Acute berylliosis, Beryllium granulomatosis, Lung carcinoma (?) (Exposure: Mining, manufacturing)
column27: >- Moldy hay: Farmer's lung (Exposure: Farming)
column29: >- Bagasse: Bagassosis (Exposure: Manufacturing wallboard, paper)
column31: >- Bird droppings: Bird-breeder's lung (Exposure: Bird handling)
column33: >- Cotton, flax, hemp: Byssinosis (Exposure: Textile manufacturing)

column1: Ground-glass appearance on HRCT is seen in which of the following conditions?

Silicosis on HRCT shows a ground-glass appearance. Silicosis is due to the inhalation of crystalline silicon dioxide (silica) seen in individuals employed in sandblasting or rock mining. Macrophages phagocytose inhaled silica particles, thereby activating and releasing inflammatory mediators (IL-1, IL-8) that cause fibroblast recruitment. Microscopy reveals coalescent nodules of whorled collagen fibers surrounded by a peripheral zone of silica-laden macrophages. HRCT shows a ""crazy paving"" pattern due to interlobular septal thickening on the background of ground-glass opacity.

Asbestosis: X-ray shows peripheral reticular opacities predominantly in the lower zones. It predominantly affects the lower lobes of the lung, in contrast to other forms of pneumoconiosis, which affect the upper lobes.
N/A - This is the correct option. See 'Explanation' row.

Anthracosis/coal workers' pneumoconiosis: This is a pulmonary condition seen in coal miners. The inhaled carbon pigment is engulfed by alveolar or interstitial macrophages, which accumulate in the connective tissue. Initially, it causes simple coal workers pneumoconiosis with little or no pulmonary dysfunction. With continued exposure, lung tissue undergoes progressive massive fibrosis which is called complicated coal workers pneumoconiosis. The upper lobes of the lungs are commonly involved. Simple coal workers' pneumoconiosis appears as small round nodular opacities with an occasional appearance of reticular or reticulonodular opacities. Compared to silicosis, the nodules in CWP tend to have less well-defined margins and a more granular appearance.

Byssinosis: Caused by cotton dust, it can induce occupational asthma. It is characterized clinically by occasional (early-stage) and then regular (late-stage) chest tightness toward the end of the first day of the workweek - Monday chest tightness.
- Coal dust: Anthracosis, Macules, Progressive massive fibrosis, Caplan syndrome (Exposure: Coal mining (particularly hard coal))
- Silica: Silicosis, Caplan syndrome (Exposure: Metal casting work, sandblasting, hard rock mining, stone cutting, others)

- Asbestos: Asbestosis, Pleural plaques, Caplan syndrome, Mesothelioma, Carcinoma of the lung, larynx, stomach, colon (Exposure: Mining, milling, manufacturing, and installation and removal of insulation)
- Beryllium: Acute berylliosis, Beryllium granulomatosis, Lung carcinoma (?) (Exposure: Mining, manufacturing)
- Bird droppings: Bird-breeder's lung (Exposure: Bird handling)
- Cotton, flax, hemp: Byssinosis (Exposure: Textile manufacturing)
